whetstone
whet stone
    A whetstone is a gray stone from SlashEM that can remove rust
    (including corrosion) and negative enchantments (up to +0) from
    an edged weapon or a pick- axe. This action requires a source of
    water. Stand at some water and apply the whetstone.

    In HackEM whetstone have been overhauled to be more useful.

    The water sources that are available include puddles, pools,
    moats, sewage, rust traps, sinks, and toilets.

    If you are carrying water and no dungeon water is available, you
    will be prompted for a potion to use. If you use your bottled
    water, there is a 1d7 chance of using it up on each attempt.

    The whetstone's beatitude determines the chance of success.
    (Same for artifacts and non-artifacts)
    stone               chance of success
    blessed whestone    1/3
    uncursed whetstone  1/4
    cursed whestone     0
    other gray stone    0

    Blessed whetstones can also enchant non-corroded, uncursed,
    +0 weapons up to +1. (This might take a little longer because you
    need to pass a coin flip after your sharpening roll succeeds)

    Cursed whetstones instead have a chance of inflicting rust damage
    to your weapon. They will never sharpen.

    If you fail, you can try again. If you always fail, your gray
    stone is not a whetstone. If you succeed, you remove one level
    of rust; or if there was no rust, you remove one point of
    negative enchantment.

    When rubbed on an iron weapon with no water available, the
    whetstone will give the message "You need some water when you use
    that."

    If your gray stone is not a whetstone, then you will try to
    sharpen the edge, but your attempt will always fail.
healthstone
health stone
    A healthstone is a gray stone that modifies a player's heal rate.
    Blessed or uncursed healthstones increase it, cursed healthstones
    decrease it.

    Healthstones are always generated cursed.

    Unlike luckstones, healthstones are cumulative - two blessed
    healthstones are better than one. To be precise, you have a health
    recovery bonus which is 2 for each blessed healthstone in your main
    inventory, plus 1 for each uncursed healthstone, minus 2 for each
    cursed healthstone. This bonus is added to your level and
    constitution when calculating how fast or how much you heal, i.e.
    if you carry 2 blessed healthstones at level 1 you will regenerate
    every 7th turn (as at level 5) instead of every 15th, and at level
    29 you will regenerate 1d24 HP instead of 1d20 (provided your
    constitution is 20).
