	  more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating a trap.

	Engraving: Burn.
wand of cancellation
	Emits a beam which cancels any monsters or objects it hits.
	Monsters are entitled to a resistance check against the effect.

	The wand of cancellation has a number of complicated effects.
	Among these effects, it will:
	    - uncurse and unbless items
	    - neutralize enchantments and charges of most items
	    - change most potions into water; sickness and see invisible
	      into fruit juice; booze and oil just become uncursed
	    - blank scrolls and spellbooks
	    - neutralize the special attacks of many monsters
	    - kill a clay golem instantly by erasing its writing

	Putting a charged wand of cancellation (or a bag containing a
	wand of cancellation) into a bag of holding will cause a magical
	explosion that will destroy the bag and scatter its contents in
	a roughly 10 by 10 area. Breakable items are subject to breakage
	from the force of the explosion.

	Zapping a bag of holding, however, will either unbless or uncurse
	it, and will have no effect on the contents.

	Zapping self: You will cancel all items carried in your inventory
	  (except wands of cancellation).

	Breaking:
	- Cause an explosion that deals 1 to (4 x charges) damage and also
	  cancels all monsters and objects in a 3x3 square around you.
	  An Anti-Magic Trap may be created when this wand is broken.
	  The more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating the trap.

	Engraving: Dust
	- Engraving over a writing in the dust gives the message "The
	  engraving on the <floor> vanishes!" This can be either a wand
	  of cancellation, make invisible, or teleportation.
wand of cold
	Zapping the wand in a given direction emits a ray of ice.
	- Deals 6d6 damage to non-cold resistant targets, with a +6d3 bonus
	  if the monster has fire resistance.
	- Monsters hit have a 1/3 chance of any potions in their
	  inventory freezing and shattering.

	Effects:
	- The ray bounces when it hits walls or targets with reflection;
	  it will also freeze any moat of water it travels over into ice,
	  and lava is cooled and solidified into normal rock.
	- Destroys doors

	Zapping self:
	- You take 12d6 damage, depending on how much cold resistance you
	  have. Your items are also subject to cold damage.

	Breaking:
	- Creates an explosion of cold dealing (8 x charges) damage.
	  An Ice Trap may be created when this wand is broken. The more
	  charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating the trap.

	Engraving: Dust.
	- Engraving over a burned engraving will make it vanish.
wand of create horde
	Zapping or engraving with it creates 4-11 monsters.

	- When a monster zaps it, creates 6-10 monsters.

	Breaking:
	- Creates an explosion dealing (8 x charges) damage and creates
	  monsters around you.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of create monster
	Zapping or engraving with it creates:
	- one monster (22/23 chance)
	- or 2-9 monsters (1/23 chance)

	- the monster level of each will be consistent with what is
	  normally created.
	- Even in the former case, a group of monsters may be created
	  if that monster often appears in large groups, such as hill orcs.

	Breaking:
	- Creates an explosion causing from 1 to (4 x charges) damage and
	  surrounds the player with monsters.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of death
	Zapping it in any direction fires a ray of death that instantly
	kills almost any monster it hits in its path, including the player.
	- As with all ray-type wands, it can rebound, and there is a
	  chance that it will miss.

	- Death, all major demons, all nonliving monsters, and monsters
	  with player-type magic resistance are completely unaffected;
	  Death in particular will actually be healed and become stronger.
	- Conversely, Pestilence and Famine are still susceptible.
	- Having reflection will prevent instant-death, but monsters/
	players will still take damage from the ray.

	- Wands of death can be recharged only once.

	Zapping self:
	- Zapping a wand of death directly at yourself results in
	  instadeath, even if you have magic resistance or reflection
	  — unless you are polymorphed into any of the unaffected
	  monsters mentioned above.

	Breaking:
	- Creates a magical explosion that deals (16 x charges) damage;
	  although referred to as a "death field" in the associated
	  message, magic resistance is not necessary to survive this
	  explosion.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of digging
	Zapping in a given direction produces a ray that can dig open a
	corridor of several squares through solid rock and walls,
	destroying any doors in its path; the ray has no effect on
	boulders.

	- Zapping upward causes a rock to fall from the ceiling and bonk
	  you on the head unless you are underwater.
	- Zapping downward creates a hole, and doing this on an
	  undiggable floor creates a pit. Unless you are levitating,
	  flying, or else happen to escape, you will fall in. Doing so on
	  a headstone always creates a pit on the square and unearths the
	  contents of that grave.
	- Zapping the wand in a maze level now works as it normally would
	  (no longer restricted to 1 square)
	- Zapping a boulder will vaporize it.
	- the ray has no effect on undiggable walls and rock.

	- Zapping the wand while being engulfed by a non-whirly monster
	  halves the monster's current HP and expels you.
	- Rays from a wand of digging will also halve the current HP of
	  "stony" monsters, including xorns, earth elementals, gargoyles
	  and stone golems.
	- Razing the walls and/or doors of Minetown will anger the watch.

	Breaking:
	- Creates an explosion causing from 1 to (4 x charges) damage.
	  Creates pits or holes on your square and the eight squares
	  around you, with the exception of undiggable floors and stairs,
	  boulders or traps. This can also destroy altars and thrones.
	  Any liquid will immediately flow in and fill the pits and holes.

	Engraving: Engraving type.
	- Any text engraved with a wand of digging is as durable as text
	  engraved with a weapon or hard gem - this makes it as effective
	  as an athame and slightly less effective than a wand of fire or
	  lightning for engraving Elbereth.
wand of draining
	Casts an unreflectable beam which drains a level from its target
	monster. Like the spellbook, it also drains enchantment (one point
	at a time) from armor and weapons, and charges from rings, wands,
	and chargeable tools.

	- The only protection against these wands is drain resistance.

	Zapping self: You lose a level unless you possess Drain Resistance.

	Breaking:
	- Creates an explosion dealing (8 x charges) damage; anything
	  caught in the explosion loses a level and objects are also
	  subject to draining.

	Engraving: Dust.
	- When engraved with, if there is a pre-existing message, it will
	  erase part, or possibly all, of it. This generally produces the
	  message "The engraving looks different now" which is shared with
	  the wand of polymorph.  If the pre-existing engraving is
      sufficiently short, the wand will instead give a message about
      the engraving disappearing; to avoid this ambiguity with the
      other wands that do that, dust-engrave moderately long messages
      before engrave-testing unidentified wands.
wand of enlightenment
	Zapping this wand grants you enlightenment: you see your properties
	and exercise wisdom.

	Breaking: No effects.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of extra healing
	Zapping yourself:
	- Heals 6d8 HP, up to the maximum.
	- Cures hallucination, blindness, and deafness.
	- If not cursed, this also cures sickness.
	- Exercises strength and constitution.

	Zapping a monster:
	- Heals 5d4 HP, +10 if the wand is blessed or cursed.
	- This means that a cursed wand of extra healing is more potent
	  than an uncursed wand.
	- If not cursed, cures a monster's sickness.
	- If zapped at a zombie, it instead inflicts damage equal.

	Breaking: No effects.

	Engraving: Dust. Shares the same message as a wand of healing:
	  "The bugs on the floor look healthier!"
wand of fear
	When zapped or engraved with, this wand scares monsters around
	you in a similar fashion to reading a scroll of scare monster.

	cursed:
	-  If monsters are fleeing, they stop.
	- If monsters are paralyzed or sleeping, they wake up and are
	able to move.
	- 80% of the time a cursed wand zaps you with fear as well.

	Breaking:
	- When broken, the explosion does no damage but instead scares
	  you for 5-15 turns.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of fire
	Zapping the wand in a given direction emits a ray of fire which
	deals 6d6 damage to non-fire resistant targets, with a +7 bonus
	if the monster has cold resistance.

	- Monsters/players hit with this ray may have their inventory set
	  aflame: potions may boil, scrolls and spellbooks may burn, and
	  organic armor may smoulder.
	- The ray bounces when it hits walls or targets with reflection;
	- It can melt any squares of ice it travels over, destroy any
	  doors it collides with and evaporates pools of water.

	In an emergency where you are afflicted with sliming, zapping the
	wand at yourself can save you.

	Breaking:
	- Results in an explosion dealing from 1 to (4 x charges) damage.
	- A Fire Trap may be created when this wand is broken. The more
	  charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating the trap.

	Engraving: Burn.
	- A popular means of engraving Elbereth - such engravings are
	  permanent and can only be removed by magical means.
wand of healing
	- Zapping yourself will heal 5d6 HP, up to the maximum and will
	  exercise strength.
	- If not cursed, this cures blindness and deafness.
	- If blessed, also cures sickness.

	- Zapping a monster will heal 5d2 HP, +5 if the wand is blessed
	  or cursed(a cursed wand is more potent than an uncursed wand.)
	- If not blessed, cures a monster's sickness.
	- If zapped at a zombie, it instead inflicts damage.

	Breaking: No effects.

	Engraving: Dust.
	- Shares the same message as a wand of extra healing:
	  "The bugs on the floor look healthier!"
wand of light
	- When zapped or engraved with, this wand lights an area with a
	  radius of 5.
	- If cursed however, the surrounding area will be darkened instead.

	Breaking:
	- Results in an explosion dealing from 1 to (4 x charges) damage,
	  with the hero being blinded for (n + 1)d25 turns, with n being the
	  number of remaining charges. The same area is lit as when the
	  wand is zapped; surrounding monsters may also be blinded, and
	  gremlins take damage.

	Engraving: Dust.

	Note: Unlike in EvilHack, this wand does not blind or anger
	peaceful monsters when zapped while they are in the radius of light.
wand of lightning
	Zapping the wand in a given direction shoots a ray of lightning.
	- Deals 6d6 damage to non-shock resistant targets;
	- also blinds targets in its line of fire for d50 (more) turns
	  with a cap of 127,
	- may also destroy any rings, wands or amulets in their inventory
	  unless they have reflection.
	- The ray bounces when it hits walls or targets with reflection;
	  being hit by a rebound will blind you for (ulevel / 2 + 1)d50
	  (more) turns.

	- Only the ring of shock resistance and the wand of lightning
	  itself are immune to destruction by shock damage (other sources
	  of shock damage include chest traps, a returning Mjollnir,
	  energy vortices or electric eels.)

	Zapping self:
	- You are blinded for 0-99 (more) turns in addition to the
	  normal shock damage.

	Breaking:
	- Creates an explosion that deals (16 x charges) damage to
	  yourself and all monsters on the surrounding squares. Your
	  inventory is subject to the same effects as though you were
	  zapped with the wand, i.e. your rings and wands may explode.
	- A Magic Beam Trap may be created when this wand is broken. The
	  more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating a trap.

	Engraving: Burn.
	- Like a wand of fire, this burns text into the ground; however,
	  doing so will blind you for d50 (more) turns. You can avoid
	  this by cancelling the prompt when asked what to engrave.
wand of locking
	A wand of locking will close and lock chests and doors.
	- If the door or the lock is broken, it will be repaired.
	- If the doorway has no door at all, a door will be created.
	  (If there is something in the doorway, the spell will not work.)
	- Drawbridges will be closed.

	- The effects of a wand of locking are the same as those of the
	  spellbook of wizard lock; see further information at wizard lock.

	Breaking: No effects.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of magic missile
	Zapping the wand in a given direction will do a fixed 2d6 damage
	to monsters in its path (unlike the spell of magic missile which
	will deal scaling damage with your skill and level).
	- the ray can rebound off walls and hit targets repeatedly.
	- Magic resistance negates this damage. Reflection partially
	  reduces this damage.

	Breaking:
	- Results in an explosion of magic missiles dealing (4 x charges)
	  damage. A Magic Trap may be created when this wand is broken.
     The more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating
     the trap.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of make invisible
	- Zapping this wand at a monster makes them invisible.
	- Zapping this wand at a peaceful monster will anger it.

	- If you zap yourself, you become invisible for:
	        (charges)d250 (more) turns.

	 - Zapping the wand downward will make any engraving on that
	   square disappear, as does engraving with it.

	Cursed wand of invisibility:
	- makes its target visible if already invisible,
	- has a 50% chance of aggravating monsters if zapped at yourself
	  while invisible.
	- If the target is visible, nothing happens.

	- Wearing a mummy wrapping protects against any effects from this
	  wand.

	Breaking:
	- Affects you and surrounding monsters with the zap effect
	  (dependent on beatitude).

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of nothing
	True to its name, the wand does absolutely nothing when zapped,
	engraved with, or broken by applying. Nevertheless, it has
	charges like any other wand.

	- A wand of nothing can either be non-directional, giving no
	  feedback whatsoever when zapped, or prompt for a direction,
	  then do nothing with it; each variant is equally likely.
	- The variant is randomly determined per-game, not per-item, so
	  if you find a non-directional wand of nothing, all other wands
	  of nothing in that game will also be non-directional. Whether
	  the wand is directional or not determines how many starting
	  charges it has (4-8 if directional, 11-15 if non-directional).

	- A wand of nothing is non-magical, and so doesn't lose its
	  charges to cancellation. As the only non-magical type of wand,
	  it will usually turn into a magical wand when polymorphed.

	- Note that the message "Nothing happens." isn't associated
	  specifically with the wand of nothing, but with any wand that's
	  out of charges. A wand of nothing only produces this message
	  when it happens to be out of charges.

	Engraving: Dust
wand of opening
	Can be used to unlock doors and containers, escape engulfing
	monsters, and remove punishment.
	- The effect is identical to that of the spell knock.

	On monsters:
	- Monster regurgitates the player if engulfed.
	- Removes monster's saddle, if worn, dropping it on the monster's
	  square (including your steed's saddle if you zap downward while
	  riding).
	- Regardless, if the zap strikes any monster, the monster does
	  not necessarily get an immediate chance to attack the player,
	  as it would with most spell strikes.

	On movable objects:
	- Striking a punished player's chain (but not the ball) will
	  unpunish you.
	- Unlocks large boxes, chests, and iron safes ("Klick!") and
	  fixes the lock if broken.

	On you:
	- If you are punished, you will receive the message "Your chain
	  quivers for a moment.", and the wand will be identified.

	On immovable objects
	- Reveals and unlocks hidden doors, and unlocks non-hidden doors.
	  The door remains closed.
	- Interrupts attempts to break down a door with a pickaxe or
	  mattock, and repairs the door.
	- If you zap up or down while on a closed portcullis (possible
	  with phasing), it will open.
	- Opens drawbridges.
	- Triggers trapdoors and falling rock traps (only if someone
	  stands on the trap).
	- Releases you or a monster from a bear trap or a web. The
	  monster may be pacified if adjacent.

	Breaking:
	- No explosion. A Trap Door may be created when this wand is
	  broken. The more charges on the wand the higher the chance of
	  creating the trap.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of poison gas
	Similar to the poison breath attack of a green dragon, zapping
	this wand shoots a ray of poison gas.
	- Monsters hit by the initial ray take 6d6 poison damage.
	- The ray leaves a trail of poison gas that lingers for a few
	  turns before dissapating.
	- The acid ray can rebound off walls.
	- Poison resistance negates this damage, as does unbreathing.
	- Doors hit by the ray will be rotted away.

	Breaking:
	- Results in a 3x3 cloud of poison gas centered around the player.
	- A Magic Beam Trap may be created when this wand is broken. The
	  more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating a trap.

	Engraving: Dust.
	- Creates a single cloud of poison gas when engraving.
wand of polymorph
	- Zapping the wand in a direction will polymorph any monsters or
	  items in its path.
	- Zapping the wand at yourself will polymorph you, ignoring magic
	  resistance.
	- Monsters can zap this wand at themselves, but mercifully, this
	  will not generate out-of-depth monsters.

	- Wands of polymorph are immune to polymorphing from other sources,
	  such as a potion of polymorph.

	Breaking:
	- Causes an explosion that deals 1 to (4 x charges) damage and
	  polymorphs monsters and items on affected squares; this
	  ignores magic resistance for the player.
	-  A Polymorph Trap may be created when this wand is broken. The
	  more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating the trap.

	Engraving: Dust
	- If an engraving already exists on your square, this wand will
	  instead transform the writing into a random rumor.
wand of probing
	- A wand of probing can give you information about a monster, or
	  the contents of a container.
	- When zapped, it will probe all targets in the path of its beam
	  It also has other uses.

	- In general, wands of probing act much like stethoscopes.
	- Zapping one prompts the player for a direction, and if there is
	  a suitable target, shows the name, alignment, level, HP, AC,
	  and status of the target.
	- Like a stethoscope, it does not anger peaceful targets.
	- Unlike a stethoscope, it is a directional beam, allowing the
	  remote assessment of the target, and it will also show the
	  inventory of the target.

	Breaking: No effects.

	Engraving: Dust.
wand of secret door detection
	When zapped, the wand has the same effect as a spell of detect
	unseen: it detects all undiscovered secret doors, mimics, and
	traps in a radius of 8 squares in line-of-sight upon
	zapping/engraving.

	- It will also show the location of submerged creatures in pools.
	- On the Plane of Air only, the wand also penetrates clouds.

	- Nearby monsters that you can't see due to invisibility will be
	  revealed as I.
	- Marks on spaces without monsters are removed, and monsters that
	  are hiding will be revealed.

	Breaking:
	- Chance of detecting traps and magic portals
	- Requires at least 2 charges to be successful, the more charges
	  the higher the chance of a successful detection.

	Engraving: Dust.
	- Engraving with the wand will only auto-identify it if any of
      these things are present; otherwise, it gives no message.
wand of sleep
	When zapped, it emits a sleep ray
	- puts monsters it hits to sleep for 6d25 turns, unless they resist.
	- Rays of sleep can bounce from walls and unrevealed secret doors,
	  but are absorbed by non-secret or discovered secret doors.
	- If you zap yourself, you are put to sleep for 1d50 turns (the
	  amount of sleep resistance you have can reduce this)
	Breaking:
	- A Sleeping Gas Trap may be created when this wand is broken. The
	  more charges on the wand the higher the chance of creating the
	  trap.

	Engraving: Dust.
	- When engraving, this wand gives the same message as a wand of
	  death. If the wand was not generated in a monster's inventory,
	  the odds are 6:1 for it being sleep.
wand of slow monster
	This wand inflicts slowness on monsters (makes them take more
	turns to move or attack).

	Monsters have a chance to resist the wand's effect, given by
			MR / (112 - difficulty)

	- If the monster does not resist, it becomes slow (2/3 of normal
	  movement speed), or normal speed if it was previously fast. If
	  you were engulfed by a whirly monster (vortex or air elemental),
